<HL> Most Midsized Cars
Incur Over $1,000
Of Damage in Test
---
By Laurie McGinley
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 02/26/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GM F HMC TOYOY
AUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but two of 22 midsized cars put through four low-speed test crashes designed to gauge bumper strength sustained damages exceeding $1,000, a highway group backed by the insurance industry said. 

   The cars were crashed four times at five miles per hour. 
"As a group," said Brian O'Neill, president of the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, the Washington-based group that tested the cars, "they did very poorly. 
There should be only minimum damage in such tests." 

   General Motors Corp.'s new Chevrolet Corsica incurred the least amount of damage -- $419 -- in the four crashes, the institute said. 
The next best competitor, the Toyota Camry, sustained damages totaling $866, while the Honda Accord DX, which did the worst, had $2,030 in damages. 

   Many of the more expensive cars tested had the more costly damages. 
All of the six worst performers had a manufacturer's suggested base price exceeding $10,000. 
The suggested base price for the Honda Accord, for example, is $10,625, while the Pontiac 6000, which sustained a total of $2,004 in damages in the tests, costs $10,499. 

   The Ford Taurus GL, which has a manufacturer's recommended price of $11,622, sustained damages totaling $1,945. 
The Mercury Sable GS, which has a $12,340 price tag, had damages of $1,571. 

   Priced at $8,995, the Chevrolet Corsica was one of the least expensive cars tested. 
The Toyota Camry is priced at $10,998. 
The Buick Skylark, which had damages of $1,024, and carries a suggested base price of $9,915, had the third-lowest damage total. 
Next was the Oldsmobile Firenza, which sustained damages of $1,125, and has an $8,449 base price. 

   The four tests were a frontal crash into a barrier, a rear crash into a barrier, a frontal crash into a barrier at an angle and a rear crash into a pole. 
All the cars tested were 1987 models, except for the Corsica, which was a 1988 model. 

   Mr. O'Neill said the extensive damage that resulted from the tests underscores the need for tougher federal bumper standards. 
In 1982, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration eased a requirement that cars be able to withstand damage to the vehicle and suffer only minimal damage to the bumper at 5 mph. 
Its action lowered the standard to 2.5 mph. 

   Officials at the safety agency say the weaker rule, on balance, benefits consumers. 
They argue that bumpers required by the 5 mph standard add to the car price, are more expensive to replace and increase fuel costs because they are heavier than less damage-resistant bumpers. 

   In Dearborn, Mich., Robert H. Munson, Ford's director of automotive safety, said "the best evidence" of the strength of the bumpers on the Taurus and Sable and of the cars' overall damage resistance is "the fact that the two largest auto insurance companies . . . and most other insurance companies offer significant discounts for collision and comprehensive coverage on 1987 Taurus and Sable models." 

   In a prepared statement, he added that "actual accident statistics compiled by the Highway Loss Data Institute, which is funded by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, show that loss payments for Taurus and Sable are 25% and 30%, respectively, below the average loss payments for all 1986-model passenger cars." 

   Mr. Munson said the Taurus and Sable "five-miles-an-hour bumpers" performed "as expected" in the Institute's tests, noting that they "incurred no damage during the five-miles-an-hour perpendicular barrier-crash portions of the test." 
He added, "The IIHS bumper test results are distorted, however, by the five-miles-an-hour 'McDonald's pole test,' which simulates a kind of accident that is relatively rare in the real world." 

   A GM spokesman in Detroit said the No. 1 auto maker was "pleased with the Chevrolet Corsica's performance" and noted that "four of the top five performers" in the test were GM products. 
He declined to comment on the performance of the Century and 6000. 

   In Detroit, a Honda spokesman declined to comment. 

