<HL> GM Moves Up Date
For Idling Of Plant,
Citing Slow Sales
---
By Dale D. Buss
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 05/19/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GM
AUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN>
<DATELINE> DETROIT  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said it plans to close temporarily most of its assembly plant here more than a month earlier than previously planned because of slow sales of several luxury-car models built at the factory. 

   GM said it now plans tentatively to shut down its state-of-the-art, two-year-old factory here, known as the "Poletown" plant, on June 26, idling about 2,500 workers until its reopening in late August. 
During the closure, the company will retool the plant for styling changes in the new fall model of the Cadillac Eldorado, which the plant builds in addition to several other GM luxury models, including the Cadillac Seville, Oldsmobile Toronado and Buick Riviera. 

   Stopping production of these 1987 models earlier than planned represents a setback for the company. 
When GM introduced the front-wheel-drive models in the fall of 1985, they were hailed as vehicles that would keep GM strong in the expensive-car market for years. 
But many consumers ignored the new products, partly because their styling was similar to less expensive GM cars and they were smaller. 
They have sold at roughly only half the rate of the models they replaced. 

   Besides underscoring the continuing problems of these cars, GM's announcement also shows that the No. 1 auto maker's recent problems in generating sales across its product line aren't easing much. 
Just last week, GM said it plans to close temporarily six other assembly plants and to lay off about 30,000 hourly workers because of slow sales, in the latest of its frequent rounds of plant shutdowns this year. 

   GM had opened the Poletown plant with much fanfare about laser-inspection systems and other high-technology devices that it was introducing there. 
But in addition to encountering resistance to the cars built there, GM also soon saw the plant run into a variety of technical snafus, which the company has spent the last year correcting. 

</TEXT>
