<HL> GM Increases '89 Model Prices From 4% to 8% --- Company Says Rise Is 2.9%, Listing Former Options As Standard Equipment </HL>
<AUTHOR> Joseph B. White (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GM </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<DATELINE> DETROIT  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. is raising the base prices of most 1989 cars and light trucks between 4% and 8%, and is pressing a strategy that makes it more attractive to buy cars that are relatively loaded with options. 

   The No. 1 auto maker, in an announcement Friday, billed the average price increase for 1989 cars as 2.9%. 
But GM adjusted for the inclusion as standard equipment of features that were sold as options last year, and also adjusted for the fact that it isn't raising the prices of equipment that remains optional. 

   Excluding this latter adjustment, the actual prices of many popular 1989 models will go up considerably more than 2.9%, even when allowances are made for new standard equipment. 

   For example, the lowest priced 1989 Pontiac Grand Prix will cost $13,899, up 10.8%, or $1,360, from the 1988 base model price of $12,539. 
The Grand Prix, the best-selling of GM's new line of midsized cars, will now have air conditioning as standard equipment. 
Last year, 99% of Grand Prix customers bought air conditioning as a $775 option, a GM spokesman said. 
So on a comparably equipped basis, the Grand Prix's base price is up 3% for 1989. 

   The base price for the 1989 Buick Regal, the Grand Prix's sister car, will rise 14.1% to $14,214. 
Adjusting for new standard equipment, the 1989 Regal's base price is still $518, or 3.8%, higher than the base 1988 model. 

   The 1989 Corsica sedan, one of GM's best-selling cars, will have a base price of $9,985, up 4.5% from last year's base price, and up 3.6% from the $9,642 price of the comparably equipped 1988 model. 

   GM is cutting the prices on a few models, such as the compact Oldsmobile Cutlass Calais. 
The Cutlass Calais's 1989 base price of $9,995 is 3.1% less than the base 1988 version. 

   GM said its price increases reflect "the partial recovery of higher material, labor and other costs." 
But GM's 1989 pricing strategy also is aimed at two broader goals. 
It cuts the number of variations of each model the company has to build, and therefore helps GM cut manufacturing costs. 
And it helps GM push customers toward buying more profitable options. 

   For instance, a 1989 Camaro RS with a package of options that includes air conditioning, four-speed automatic transmission, power door locks, AM/FM-cassette stereo, tinted glass and rear window defogger will list for $12,227, or 5.3% less than the comparably equipped 1988 model. 

   But a buyer who wants a base 1989 Camaro RS will pay 4.5% more for that car than for the base 1988 Camaro RS. Even adjusting for the additional equipment added to the 1989 base car, the $11,495 price represents a 3.8% increase over the comparably equipped 1988 model. 

   In addition to the base price increases, GM is also adding $25 to the destination charges it tacks on to each vehicle delivered. 

   GM's price disclosure follows announcements by Chrysler Corp. that it expects to raise base prices an average of 3.9%, or about 2.3% when adjusted for additional standard equipment. 
Ford Motor Co. earlier this month said it is raising the base prices of a half-dozen older models an average of 3%. 
Ford hasn't announced its final prices yet. 

   GM's 1989 pricing strategy builds on moves last year to justify higher prices by building more standard equipment into the base models. 

   Company officials say building popular options in as standard equipment will mean that base model prices more honestly reflect the prices customers actually will pay for cars. 

   "Under 5% buy base cars. 
That's an artifact, and customers know that," Shirley Young, GM's vice president for consumer market development, said in a recent interview. 

   But for 1989, GM officials are conceding that some of the price increases are simply "economic adjustments." 
The base price of the full-size Chevrolet pickup truck, for instance, will rise 4.5% in 1989 to $10,335, compared with $9,894 in 1988. 
No new equipment is included, a Chevrolet spokeswoman said. 

   GM isn't raising the base prices of its least expensive and most expensive cars, the Pontiac LeMans and the Cadillac Allante. 
The Allante, the flagship of the Cadillac division, has a base price of $56,533, and hasn't sold well. 
The LeMans, made in South Korea, has a base price of $6,399. 

   The base price of a domestically built entry level model, the two-door Chevrolet Cavalier, will increase 5.4% in 1989 to $7,375 from $6,995, the Chevrolet spokeswoman said. 

   Because GM announced its 1989 prices to the public Friday afternoon before giving details to its dealers, dealers late last week said they needed to know more before making any comment. 

</TEXT>
