<HEAD>German Automakers Try Incentives To Lure U.S. Buyers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-European Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DEDERICHS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buffeted by a cheaper dollar and Japanese
competition, European carmakers are hoping to hold on to their
lucrative slice of the American market. Two of them are trying new
incentives to keep Americans buying.
   At present, the Europeans have a 5.1 percent share of the
American mmarket, compared to 18.6 percent for the Japanese.
   ``Fly to Europe on Mercedes-Benz,'' says a newspaper
advertisement of the West German automaker. The company offers a
single business-class seat or two coach-class seats to anybody who
orders a Mercedes in the United States.
   It is the first time American buyers have been offered a free
trip to pick up the prestige autos at the factory in Stuttgart.
   ``We offer them a luncheon and, if they want, a factory tour,''
said Fred Chapman, spokesman of Mercedes-Benz North America in
Montvale, N.J.
   Since the beginning of the advertising campaign earlier this
year, about 700 Americans have accepted the offer, Chapman said.
   With factory deliveries, buyers save $3,500 for the lower-priced
Mercedes to almost $10,000 for the luxury model, Chapman added.
   After the buyer completes his European vacation, the company
arranges to ship the car without charge to the U.S. dealer who
handles customs arrangements and other paperwork.
   For Mercedes-Benz cars delivered new in the United States,
prices range from $29,190 for the 190E model with manual
transmission to $77,065 for the 560 SEC.
   Last year, 89,000 Mercedes were sold on the American market. In
the first six months of 1988, sales were steady at 44,066.
   Porsche, the West German builder of sports cars, lost some
business this year mostly because of the weak dollar. ``That made
our cars more expensive and less affordable,'' said Martha Mckinley
from the company's U.S. headquarters in Reno, Nevada.
   Porsche sold 12,824 cars in the first six months of 1987, but
sales declined to 8,807 in the same period of this year.
   The company is now trying to recapture some ground with an
incentive program. The company's Trust-Tourist Delivery program
offers discounts between 7 and 10 percent, depending on the model,
for all models ordered in the United States and picked up in West
Germany.
   Prices range from $26,560 for the Porsche 924 to $69,380 for the
Porsche 928.
   The company sees its main competition from Japanese cars and
from its German rival.
   ``In the lower-priced cars it's the Japanese product. When it
comes to the expensive models, we have to fight Mercedes,'' she
said.
   The Italian auto giant Fiat, which sells Alfa Romeos and Lancia
cars on the American market, has similar fears. The company took
its own Fiat models off the market because of the Japanese
competition in the small-car area. Gualberto Ramieri, a Fiat
spokesman, expects that the new Alfa Romeo 164 will capture some
lost ground in America.
   The price for the car on the American market has not been fixed
yet, he added.
   In the first six months of 1988, Fiat sold 2,708 Alfa Romeos in
the United States, down from 3,422 in the same period last year.
For the whole 1988, Ramieri expects the sale of about 6,000 cars
through the company's 150 dealers across the United States.
   France's Peugeot also lost some ground in the United States. It
sold 9,320 cars last year but only 3,454 cars in the first half of
1988. Spokeswoman Kim Derderian said the company hopes a new model,
the Peugeot 405, will recapture some buyers.
   The British luxury car maker Jaguar doesn't fear sales losses.
The car with a basic price of $45,000 finds most of its admirers in
California, Florida and the bigger cities, according to company
spokesman Tom McDonald. Last year the company sold 10,028 of its
cars in the United States. McDonald expects no major changes for
this year.
   BMW, another German luxury carmaker, has no plans to offer
special incentives to U.S. buyers.
   ``We know about the free trips Mercedes offers but we have no
similar program,'' said Robert Mitchell from BMW North America. His
company sold 87,839 cars last year on the American market. Mitchell
expects the same result for this year.
