<TEXT>
   Several foreign car makers have announced price increases on their 1988 U.S. models, adding profitable luxury equipment and more powerful engines compared with the 1987 models. 

   The companies said some of their increases also reflect the continuing weakness of the U.S. dollar compared with many foreign currencies. 

   One manufacturer is cutting or freezing some prices, however, in an effort to realign its products and avoid overlap among its models. 

   BMW of North America Inc. said it is boosting base prices 1.9% to 7% on the six BMW models that go on sale by Nov. 1. 
American Honda Motor Co.'s Acura division is increasing base prices on its 1988 Legend cars 1.5% to 7.9%. 

   Peugeot Motors of America said base prices for its entire 1988 model line will rise 1% to 9.9%. 
With sales currently running about 32% below a year ago, Peugeot also said it will offer owners of its diesel-engine cars rebates of $4,000 if they purchase a new 1987-model gasoline-powered Peugeot. 

   The lone price-cutter in the latest round of announcements is Volkswagen of America Inc. 
The U.S. sales arm of West German-based Volkswagen AG said it is freezing prices on three of its Golf and Jetta subcompact cars, cutting the price of the least-expensive Jetta and introducing a new 1988 model Golf with a base price $400 lower than the lowest-price 1987 model Golf. 

   The new base Golf will start at $7,990. 
Volkswagen raised the price of the next least-expensive Golf -- the GL model -- 1.2%, or $100, to $8,490 and froze the price of the Golf GT at $9,975. 
The company said it made only minor equipment changes on the two-door Jetta, which now starts at $8,990, 6.3% below the 1987 model. 

   BMW, a unit of Bayerische Motoren Werke AG of West Germany, said its latest price increases, which cover six of its 1988 models, averaged 3.7%, or $1,450. 
BMW will announce prices for its remaining eight models when they go on sale in late November. 

   Honda said its 1988 model Acura Legend prices averaged 4.4%, or $1,016, higher than comparably equipped 1987 models. 
The U.S. unit of Japan's Honda Motor Co. said it added a more powerful engine, antilock brakes and a security system to the Legend Sedan L. 
The Sedan L equipped with automatic transmission now starts at $25,748, an increase of 7.9%, or $1,890, from the 1987 version. 

   French auto maker Peugeot S.A.'s U.S. sales unit said the weak U.S. dollar accounted for most of its 4.7%, or $988, average price increase. 
The least-expensive Peugeot, the 505 DL, will start at $15,495 when it goes on sale next month with the rest of Peugeot's 1988 product line. 
The company also increased destination charges on all cars by $10, to $385. 

   Peugeot said its $4,000 rebate should help in "enhancing the resale value" of its diesel-powered cars. 
Sales of most manufacturers' diesel-engine models have slumped over the past few years, mainly because of declining gasoline prices and quality problems in some cars that hurt the image of the engines. 
In 1984, 80% of the cars Peugeot sold here had diesel engines, but the company stopped importing those models in the 1986 model year. 

