<HEAD>NY Nightmare: Two Cars Stolen In 3 Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leo Vigil is caught in a New York City nightmare.
   Three weeks ago, his brand-new Nissan Pathfinder was stolen from
outside a Manhattan restaurant where he had taken a customer of his
tie company for dinner.
   ``The buyer was telling me about how his car had been stolen. We
walk out of the restaurant and my car's gone,'' Vigil said.
   On Monday, his other car, a 1989 Jaguar, was one of seven autos
taken at gunpoint from a Greenwich Village garage.
   ``My insurance company is totally freaking out,'' Vigil said.
His two cars were worth about $75,000.
   Two of the cars taken Monday _ a Toyota and a Honda _ were
abandoned near the garage, but the Jaguar, a BMW, a Porsche and two
other cars not yet identified were driven away.
   ``The luxury cars are very hard to steal, that's why we're
having more gunpoint robberies,'' said Sgt. Pete Baglio of the Auto
Crime Division. ``The expensive cars have alarm systems that make
them tough to get into.''
   Once stolen, ``a lot of these cars are being tagged and shipped
out of the country. They're not chopping up these cars,'' Baglio
added.
   ``It's just devastating, it really is,'' Vigil said in a
telephone interview Monday. ``It's just amazing what happens here.''
   He said he'd bought another Pathfinder and would ``hope for the
best.''
   There were 133,861 reported car thefts in the city in 1989, a
rise of 13,921 from 1988, according to police statistics.
   But nationwide, New York City ranked ninth per capita in car
thefts, after top-ranked Boston, Dallas, Detroit, San Diego,
Houston, New Orleans, Los Angeles, and Memphis, Tenn.
