<HL> Ford to Buy Aston,
Following 2 Rivals
In Prestige Market
---
By Paul Ingrassia
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 09/08/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> F EUROP
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN>
<DATELINE> DEARBORN, Mich.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said it agreed to acquire closely held Aston Martin Lagonda Ltd., the British maker of ultraluxury cars. 
Terms weren't disclosed. 

   Aston Martin, based in Newport Pagnell, England, produces fewer than 200 cars a year, with prices ranging from $145,000 to $170,000. 
The company has only 400 employees. 

   With the acquisition, Ford joins the other members of the U.S. Big Three, in buying a European auto maker specializing in limited production of extremely expensive cars. 
General Motors Corp. last year purchased Group Lotus PLC, another British company, while Chrysler Corp. recently acquired Nuova Automobili F. Lamborghini S.p.A. of Italy, which makes 400 cars a year with price tags about same as Aston Martin's. 

   The U.S. companies say they can benefit from the engineering expertise of such specialty car makers, while also providing capital to allow the European concerns to boost production and develop future models. 

   Kenneth Whipple, chairman of Ford of Europe, made those points in yesterday's announcement. 
"Ford involvement will allow Aston Martin to expand its production capabilities and fully pursue future product programs," Mr. Whipple said. 
"For Ford, it is an opportunity to enter the high-image, specialty market, where Aston Martin has earned an outstanding reputation." 

   Mr. Whipple also said that Aston Martin will "retain its individual character, identity and present management." 
Victor Gauntlett will continue as chairman of Aston Martin, which was founded in 1919. 

   Last year Ford made an unsuccessful effort to enter the European luxury market, although in a niche well below Aston Martin's. 
Ford bid to acquire Alfa Romeo S.p.A. of Italy, which makes more cars than Aston Martin, but sells them for less than $50,000. 
But Fiat S.p.A. convinced the Italian government, which held a controlling interest in Alfa Romeo, that Alfa would best be left in Italian hands. 
The government sold its Alfa stake to Fiat. 

   Aston Martin currently sells three models in the U.S. -- the Volante, the Vantage and the Lagonda. 
In addition, in Europe it sells the Saloon. 
All four are equipped with V-8 engines. 

   Ford said yesterday that each Aston Martin vehicle is in production for 16 weeks, during which it gets 20 coats of hand-rubbed paint. 
By comparison, two to three coats are standard for most cars. 
The production rate is five a week -- equivalent to about five minutes of production at a typical Ford plant. 

   Aston Martin models have been driven by secret agent James Bond in many of the Bond movies. 
In the latest Bond film, "The Living Daylights," the agent drives a 1987 Volante. 

